    <string name="building_popup_title">Boyd Orr</string>
    <string name="building_popup_text">The Boyd Orr building found next to Ashton Lane contains the majority
    of the labs used by computing science students at the university of glasgow.\n\n
    The Boyd Orr Building is named for the Nobel laureate Lord Boyd Orr of Brechin (1880-1971), Rector of
    the University from 1945 to 1947, and Chancellor of the University from 1946 to 1971.\n\n
    It was designed in 1964 by architects JL Gleave and Partners primarily as a general science building to
    act as an overflow for the overcrowded departmental buildings largely for first-year students given the
    projected 50% increase in students during the late 1960s and early 1970s.\n\n
    Sir Eric Ashby, botanist and Master of Clare College, Cambridge, officially opened the Â£1.25m Boyd Orr building on 3 October 1972.\n\n
    The interior has been largely refurbished. In 2009-2010, the two main lecture theatres were updated by crgp limited</string>
